title:
TITLE     Conopeptides from Conus striatus and Conus textile by cDNA cloning
  TITLE     The A-superfamily of conotoxins: structural and functional
            divergence
  TITLE     Phylogenetic specificity of cholinergic ligands: alpha-conotoxin SI
  TITLE     Determinants involved in the affinity of alpha-conotoxins GI and SI
            for the muscle subtype of nicotinic acetylcholine receptors
  TITLE     Cysteine-Rich alpha-Conotoxin SII Displays Novel Interactions at
            the Muscle Nicotinic Acetylcholine Receptor
  TITLE     Solution structure of alpha-conotoxin SI
comment:
On or before Apr 6, 2005 this sequence version replaced gi:84535,
            gi:117728.
            [FUNCTION] Alpha-conotoxins act on postsynaptic membranes, they
            bind to the nicotinic acetylcholine receptors (nAChR) and thus
            inhibit them (PubMed:3196703). Is active on muscle nAChR
            (IC(50)=113 nM on adult subtype
            (alpha-1-beta-1-gamma-delta/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRNG-CHRND) and
            IC(50)=142 nM on fetal subtype
            (alpha-1-beta-1-delta-epsilon/CHRNA1-CHRNB1-CHRND-CHRNE))
            (PubMed:9174364, PubMed:35357806). On mice muscle receptors, its
            higher affinity site is the alpha/delta nAChR subunit interface
            (PubMed:9174364). On Torpedo receptors, it does not distinguish
            between alpha/delta and alpha/gamma acetylcholine-binding sites
            (PubMed:9174364). In vivo, causes paralysis followed by death when
            injected into goldfish (PubMed:3196703). In contrast, has no effect
            on mice, when similar doses are intraperitoneally or
            intracerebrally injected (PubMed:3196703).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:3196703, ECO:0000269|PubMed:35357806,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:9174364}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:3196703}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:3196703}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is I (CC-C-C). Alpha3/5 pattern.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: shows no or weak inhibition on
            neuronal nAChR alpha-3-beta-2/CHRNA3-CHRNB2,
            alpha-3-beta-4/CHRNA3-CHRNB4, alpha-4-beta-2/CHRNA4-CHRNB2,
            alpha-4-beta-4/CHRNA4-CHRNB4, alpha-7/CHRNA7,
            alpha-9-alpha-10/CHRNA9-CHRNA10. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:35357806}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin A superfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=Potassium channel toxin alpha-KTx 31.1; AltName:
Full=Kbot55.
title:
TITLE     Kbot55, purified from Buthus occitanus tunetanus venom, represents
            the first member of a novel alpha-KTx subfamily
comment:
[FUNCTION] Voltage-gated potassium channel inhibitor. 1 uM of the
            native toxin inhibits rat Kv1.2/KCNA2 (100% inhibition), and
            drosophila Shaker IR/Sh (100%), human Kv1.3/KCNA3 (83%), rat
            Kv1.1/KCNA1 (32%) and rat Kv1.6/KCNA6 (21%).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:26079392}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:26079392}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:26079392}.
            [DOMAIN] Has the structural arrangement of an alpha-helix connected
            to antiparallel beta-sheets by disulfide bonds (CS-alpha/beta).
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=4128.65; Method=MALDI; Note=Average mass.;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:26079392}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] LD(50) is below 5 ug/kg by intracerebroventricular
            injection into mice. A rapid paralysis in the lower half of the
            body was observed a few minutes after the injection and after 10
            min the animals died.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not inhibit rKv1.4/KCNA4 and
            the sodium channel rNav1.4/SCN4A. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:26079392}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the short scorpion toxin superfamily.
            Potassium channel inhibitor family. Alpha-KTx 31 subfamily.

            comparison of MVIIA, SVIB and SNX-202
comment:
On or before Apr 6, 2005 this sequence version replaced gi:483140,
            gi:117754.
            [FUNCTION] Omega-conotoxins act at presynaptic membranes, they bind
            and block voltage-gated calcium channels (Cav). This toxin blocks
            N-, P- and Q-type calcium channels. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1390774}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1390774}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:1390774}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:8913308}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is VI/VII (C-C-CC-C-C).
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] On fish, this toxin causes paralysis and death on
            intramuscular injection at doses of approximately 20 pmol/g. On
            intracranial injection into mice, it causes respiratory distress at
            around 70 pmol/g mouse and is lethal at around 300 pmol/g mouse.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1390774}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin O1 superfamily.
            {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Latarcins, antimicrobial and cytolytic peptides from the venom of
            the spider Lachesana tarabaevi (Zodariidae) that exemplify
            biomolecular diversity
  TITLE     Lachesana tarabaevi, an expert in membrane-active toxins
  TITLE     Spatial structure and activity mechanism of a novel spider
            antimicrobial peptide
comment:
[FUNCTION] It has antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive
            bacteria (A.globiformis VKM Ac-1112 (MIC=0.7 uM), and B.subtilis
            VKM B-501 (MIC=0.4 uM)), Gram-negative bacteria (E.coli DH5-alpha
            (MIC=1.0 uM), E.coli MH1 (MIC=0.7 uM), and P.aeruginosa PAO1
            (MIC=6.7 uM)), and yeasts (P.pastoris GS115 (MIC=6.7 uM), and
            S.cerevisiae Y190 (MIC=54 uM)). Also has a strong hemolytic
            activity against rabbit erythrocytes. Causes paralysis, but is not
            lethal when injected into insect (M.domestica) larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:27287558}.
            [DOMAIN] The mature peptide (59-84) forms alpha-helices which
            probably disrupt target cell membranes.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16939228}.
            [PTM] Cleavage of the propeptide depends on the processing
            quadruplet motif (XXXR, with at least one of X being E).
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:27287558}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=2901.0; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=2902.7; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            02 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 29.25 +-2.0 nmol/g in blowfly (L.caesar) (at

            [FUNCTION] Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).
            This toxin potently blocks rat Nav1.4/SCN4A (IC(50)= 19-110 nM)
            (PubMed:1654319, PubMed:1326324, PubMed:10627583, PubMed:21652775,
            PubMed:30360356). It also moderately blocks rNav1.1/SCN1A (Kd=260
            nM), rNav1.2/SCN2A (IC(50)=2.7-17.8 uM), and mNav1.6/SCN8A
            (IC(50)=680 nM) (PubMed:10627583, PubMed:21652775). The inhibition
            is reversible. In vivo, induces paralysis to an isolated skeletal
            muscle preparation from frog (cutaneous pectoralis) within a few
            minutes (PubMed:2410412). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10627583,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:18950653, ECO:0000269|PubMed:21652775,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:2410412, ECO:0000269|PubMed:30360356}.

            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:6852238}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is III (CC-C-C-CC). Classified in
            the M-4 branch, since 4 residues stand between the fourth and the
            fifth cysteine residues. {ECO:0000305}.
            [PTM] Hydroxylated; hydroxylations improve the ability to block
            Nav1.4/SCN4A sodium channels but does not affect folding.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1991506, ECO:0000269|PubMed:2069951}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not or only weakly blocks
            rNav1.3/SCN3A, rNav1.5/SCN5A, rNav1.7/SCN9A (IC(50)=6.0 uM and >100
            uM), and rNav1.8/SCN10A (PubMed:10627583, PubMed:21652775).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10627583, ECO:0000269|PubMed:21652775}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin M superfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

comment:
[FUNCTION] This three-finger toxin inhibits ASIC channels. It acts
            as a gating modifier toxin by decreasing the apparent proton
            sensitivity of activation and by slightly increasing the apparent
            proton sensitivity for inactivation (PubMed:23034652). It binds
            more tightly to the closed state and to a much lesser extent the
            inactivated/desensitized state of ASIC1a isoform of ASIC1
            (PubMed:23034652). It interacts directly with the outside surface
            of the thumb domain of chicken ASIC1a (ASIC1a), but does not insert
            into the acidic pocket as suggested for mambalgin-2
            (PubMed:29872539). This binding leads to relocation of the thumb
            domain that could disrupt the acidic pocket of cASIC1a
            (PubMed:29872539). It reversibly inhibits rat ASIC1a (IC(50)=3.4-55
            nM), rat ASIC1a-ASIC2b (IC(50)=61 nM), rat ASIC1a-ASIC1b (IC(50)=72
            nM), human ASIC1a (IC(50)=127-580 nM), chicken ASIC1a (IC(50)=123.6
            nM), rat ASIC1b (IC(50)=22.2-203 nM), rat ASIC1a-ASIC2a
            (IC(50)=152-252 nM) (PubMed:23034652, PubMed:23624383,
            PubMed:25873388, PubMed:24619065, PubMed:26680001,
            PubMed:29872539). In vivo, it shows a potent naloxone-resistant
            analgesic effect against acute and inflammatory pain upon central
            and peripheral injection (PubMed:23034652). In addition, it also
            has an opioid-independent effect on both thermal and mechanical
            inflammatory pain after systemic administration and is effective
            against neuropathic pain (PubMed:26680001).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652, ECO:0000269|PubMed:23624383,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:24619065, ECO:0000269|PubMed:26680001,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:29872539}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland. {ECO:0000305}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=6555.7; Method=MALDI; Note=Average mass.;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652}.
            [PHARMACEUTICAL] Promising peptide that shows a potent analgesic
            effect against acute and inflammatory pain that can be as strong as
            morphine but resistant to naloxone, with much less tolerance and no
            respiratory distress. {ECO:0000305|PubMed:23034652}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no effect on rat ASIC2a, rat
            ASIC3, rat ASIC1a-ASIC3 and rat ASIC1b-ASIC3 channels, as well as
            on TRPV1, P2RX2 (P2X2), HTR3A (5-HT3A), Nav1.8 (SCN10A), Cav3.2
            (CACNA1H) and Kv1.2 (KCNA2) channels (PubMed:23034652). Does not
            produce motor dysfunction, apathy, flaccid paralysis, convulsions
            or death upon central injections (intrathecal or
            intracerebroventricular) in mice (PubMed:23034652).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the snake three-finger toxin family.
            Short-chain subfamily. Mambalgin sub-subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
            [WEB RESOURCE] Name=The Electron Microscopy Data Bank;
            URL='https://www.ebi.ac.uk/pdbe/entry/emdb/EMD-6900'.

definition: RecName: Full=Iota-conotoxin-like r11d; AltName: Full=R11.8.
title:
TITLE     Novel excitatory Conus peptides define a new conotoxin superfamily
  TITLE     I(1)-superfamily conotoxins and prediction of single D-amino acid
            occurrence
comment:
[FUNCTION] Iota-conotoxins bind to voltage-gated sodium channels
            (Nav) and act as agonists by shifting the voltage-dependence of
            activation to more hyperpolarized levels (By similarity). Both
            natural (L-Thr form) and synthetic (D-Thr form) peptides cause
            paralysis and death following intracranial injection and grooming
            and hypersensitivity upon intraperitoneal injection into mice. The
            L-Thr form of the peptide is 7-fold more potent than the D-Thr
            form. Both natural peptide (L-Thr form) and synthetic peptide
            (D-Thr form) are active on nerve, and on muscle. {ECO:0000250,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:17996262}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is XI (C-C-CC-CC-C-C).
            [PTM] Position 41 corresponds to a L-threonine, and not a
            D-threonine as firstly supposed.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=4399.26; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:12694387}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin I1 superfamily.
            {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Latarcins, antimicrobial and cytolytic peptides from the venom of
            the spider Lachesana tarabaevi (Zodariidae) that exemplify
            biomolecular diversity
  TITLE     Lachesana tarabaevi, an expert in membrane-active toxins
comment:
[FUNCTION] [M-zodatoxin-Lt6a]: Does not have antimicrobial activity
            against Gram-positive bacteria (A.globiformis VKM Ac-1112 (MIC>70
            uM) and B.subtilis VKM B-501 (MIC>70 uM)), Gram-negative bacteria
            (E.coli DH5-alpha (MIC>70 uM), E.coli MH1 (MIC>70 uM) and
            P.aeruginosa PAO1 (MIC>70 uM)), yeast (P.pastoris GS115 (MIC>70 uM)
            or S.cerevisiae Y190 (MIC>70 uM)). Does not have hemolytic activity
            against rabbit erythrocytes. However, it causes some conductance
            changes in planar bilayer membranes, without membrane rupture,
            suggesting a cytolytic function on other biological targets. It
            causes paralysis, but is not lethal when injected into insect
            larvae. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:16735513, ECO:0000305|PubMed:27287558}.
            [DOMAIN] The mature peptides (45-79 and 84-116) probably form
            alpha-helices which disrupt target cell membranes.
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:16735513}.
            [PTM] Cleavage of the propeptide depends on the processing
            quadruplet motif (XXXR, with at least one of X being E).
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:27287558}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [M-zodatoxin-Lt6a]: Mass=4035.1; Method=MALDI;
            Note=M-zodatoxin-Lt6a.; Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            06 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=Omega-conotoxin-like protein 1; Short=OCLP1; Flags:
Precursor.
title:
TITLE     Direct Submission
  TITLE     Novel families of toxin-like peptides in insects and mammals: a
            computational approach
  TITLE     Honey bee drones maintain humoral immune competence throughout all
            life stages in the absence of vitellogenin production
  TITLE     Direct Submission
comment:
[FUNCTION] The impact of this protein on the neuronal activity of
            the honeybee brain is not known. It does not affect apparent
            movement or hatching of blowfly larvae. However, when injected into
            fish, it induces a strong reversible paralytic effect. In addition,
            the presence of this small peptide in the hemolymph of adult drones
            together with its induction after bacterial infection suggests that
            this peptide exhibits antibacterial activity. This peptide may act
            by inhibiting ion channels. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17433819}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Highly expressed in brain. Is also found in
            hemolymph. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17433819,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22442369}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin. {ECO:0000250}.

definition:
RecName: Full=Conotoxin SIIID; AltName: Full=S3-G02; Flags:
Precursor.
title:
TITLE     Characterizing the evolution and functions of the M-superfamily
            conotoxins
  TITLE     Synthesis and characterization of alphaM-conotoxin SIIID, a
            reversible human alpha7 nicotinic acetylcholine receptor antagonist
comment:
[FUNCTION] The short synthetic peptide SIIID (range 54-74, with
            disulfide pairing 1-4, 2-5 and 3-6) reversibly inhibits human
            alpha-7/CHRNA7 acetylcholine receptor (IC(50)=880 nM)
            (PubMed:35255330). Shows a paralytic effect in fish (By
            similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P0DKQ2,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:35255330}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000305|PubMed:24080356}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:24080356}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is III (CC-C-C-CC). Classified in
            the M-1 branch, since 1 residue stands between the fourth and the
            fifth cysteine residues. {ECO:0000305}.
            [PTM] Three disulfide isomers have been synthesized and tested.
            SIIID with the disulfide pairing 1-4;2-5;3-6 is the most active.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:35255330}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: SIIID with the disulfide pairing
            1-4;2-5;3-6 shows no or very activity on sodium, potassium and
            calcium currents in rat DRG neurons. It does not show obvious
            effect on the human alpha-3-beta 4/CHRNA3-CHRNB4 nicotinic
            acetylcholine receptor. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:35255330}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin M superfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
            [CAUTION] Wang et al (2022) synthesized and tested activity on the
            short peptide 54-74. By comparison with Conotoxins SIIIA and SIIIB
            (AC P0DKQ2, and AC P0CE77) and according to pair of basic residues,
            the natural peptide may be 2 residues longer at the N-terminus
            (52-74), and may contain a pyrrolidone carboxylic acid at its
            N-terminal Gln-52. {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Intron retention as a posttranscriptional regulatory mechanism of
            neurotoxin expression at early life stages of the starlet anemone
            Nematostella vectensis
  TITLE     Concerted evolution of sea anemone neurotoxin genes is revealed
            through analysis of the Nematostella vectensis genome
  TITLE     Sea anemone genome reveals ancestral eumetazoan gene repertoire and
            genomic organization
  TITLE     Neurotoxin localization to ectodermal gland cells uncovers an
            alternative mechanism of venom delivery in sea anemones
  TITLE     Development of a rational nomenclature for naming peptide and
            protein toxins from sea anemones
  TITLE     Dynamics of venom composition across a complex life cycle
  TITLE     The Birth and Death of Toxins with Distinct Functions: A Case Study
            in the Sea Anemone Nematostella
comment:
[FUNCTION] Binds to site 3 of voltage-gated sodium channels and
            inhibits the inactivation process (PubMed:18538344). Is highly
            active on DmNav1/TipE (drosophila) and is only extremely weakly
            active on rat Nav1.4-beta-1/SCN4A-SCN1B, and on human
            Nav1.5-beta-1/SCN5A-beta-1 (PubMed:18538344). This reveals high
            specificity for arthropod over mammalian channels
            (PubMed:18538344). In vivo, when released into the medium, this
            recombinant toxin induces impaired swimming, paralysis and death of
            the crustacean A.nauplii within several hours (PubMed:22048953).
            Also causes paralysis of cherry shrimps immediately after injection
            at very low doses (PubMed:29424690). Its effect on zebrafish
            (D.rerio) larvae is also rapid, since it induces tail twitching
            accompanied by impaired swimming after 20 minutes and complete
            paralysis within 45 minutes (PubMed:22048953). It has also been
            observed to cause death of zebrafish larvae within 1 hour
            (PubMed:31134275). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [ALTERNATIVE PRODUCTS] Event=Alternative splicing; Named
            isoforms=2; Comment=Intron retention discovered for all
            transcripts, no experimental confirmation available for this
            specific sequence.; Name=1; IsoId=B1NWR6-1; Sequence=Displayed;
            Name=2; Synonyms=truncated; IsoId=B1NWR6-2; Sequence=VSP_039745.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed in ectodermal glands and in clumps
            outside of the extodermal layer (PubMed:22048953). Is not expressed
            in nematocytes (PubMed:22048953). In adult female tissues, shows
            similar expression levels in mesenteries (gametes-producing
            tissue), tentacles, pharynx and physa (PubMed:29424690).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690}.
            [DEVELOPMENTAL STAGE] Is detected in unfertilized eggs (at protein
            level) (PubMed:29424690, PubMed:31134275). Is also detected in late
            planulae, primary polyps and adults (both females and males) (at
            protein level) (PubMed:22048953, PubMed:29424690). Nv1 is
            transcribed throughout the complete life cycle and is found at
            multiple developmental stages including unfertilized eggs,
            blastulae, gastrulae, early planulae, planulae, metamorphosing
            planulae, primary polyps, juvenile polyps (2 and 4 months old),
            adult males, and adult females, with highest levels in juvenile
            polyps and adults (PubMed:18538344, PubMed:29424690). Importantly,
            Nv1 transcripts are not spliced in the embryo and planula due to
            intron retention and therefore Nv1 can be considered purely an
            adult toxin (PubMed:18538344). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 76 nmol/kg into blowfly larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Nv1 toxin seems to be encoded by 8 different genes.
            4 of them code for identical precursors, whereas 4 others code for
            very similar precursors. In the genome draft, 6 additional loci are
            also correlated to Nv1 toxin, but they are not predicted to be
            functional genes. This high similarity may be explained by
            concerted evolution.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] The primary structure of the mature peptide is
            identical in 9 entries (AC B1NWS4, AC B1NWS1, AC B1NWR6, AC P0CH90,
            AC P0CH46, AC B1NWS8, AC A7SCE5, AC B1NWR7 and AC P0CH45).
            Additional information can be found in entry AC B1NWS4.
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] [Isoform 2]: Due to an intron retention observed
            only in early life stages (embryo and planula). {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no activity on the rat brain
            channel Nav1.2a-beta-1/SCN2A-SCN1B. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemone sodium channel inhibitory
            toxin family. Type II subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
            [CAUTION] The 8 variants shown here could also be shown in the 3
            identical proteins (AC B1NWS4, AC P0CH46 and AC B1NWR7) encoded by
            the 3 different genes. {ECO:0000305}.
            [SEQUENCE CAUTION] Sequence=EDO38670.1; Type=Erroneous gene model
            prediction; Evidence={ECO:0000305}.

            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            05 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=M-zodatoxin-Lt2b; Short=M-ZDTX-Lt2b; AltName:
Full=Latarcin-2b; Short=Ltc-2b; Flags: Precursor.
title:
TITLE     Latarcins, antimicrobial and cytolytic peptides from the venom of
            the spider Lachesana tarabaevi (Zodariidae) that exemplify
            biomolecular diversity
  TITLE     Lachesana tarabaevi, an expert in membrane-active toxins
comment:
[FUNCTION] Has antimicrobial activity against both Gram-positive
            and Gram-negative bacteria, and yeasts. Also has a strong hemolytic
            activity against rabbit erythrocytes. Causes paralysis, but is not
            lethal when injected into insect (M.domestica) larvae (By
            similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q1ELU1}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:27287558}.
            [DOMAIN] The mature peptide (59-84) forms alpha-helices which
            probably disrupt target cell membranes.
            {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q1ELU7}.
            [PTM] Cleavage of the propeptide depends on the processing
            quadruplet motif (XXXR, with at least one of X being E).
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:27287558}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=2879.7; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            02 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=M-zodatoxin-Lt1a; Short=M-ZDTX-Lt1a; AltName:
Full=Latarcin-1; Short=Ltc-1; Short=Ltc1; Flags: Precursor.
title:
TITLE     Latarcins, antimicrobial and cytolytic peptides from the venom of
            the spider Lachesana tarabaevi (Zodariidae) that exemplify
            biomolecular diversity
  TITLE     Lachesana tarabaevi, an expert in membrane-active toxins
  TITLE     Three-dimensional structure/hydrophobicity of latarcins specifies
            their mode of membrane activity
comment:
[FUNCTION] Has antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive
            bacteria (A.globiformis VKM Ac-1112 (MIC=0.5 uM), and B.subtilis
            VKM B-501 (MIC=1.0 uM)), Gram-negative bacteria (E.coli DH5-alpha
            (MIC=1.0 uM), E.coli MH1 (MIC=0.7 uM), and P.aeruginosa PAO1
            (MIC=4.1 uM)), and yeasts (P.pastoris GS115 (MIC=17 uM), and
            S.cerevisiae Y190 (MIC>33 uM)). Has a moderate hemolytic activity
            against rabbit erythrocytes. Causes paralysis, but is not lethal
            when injected into insect (M.domestica) larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:16735513}.
            [DOMAIN] The mature peptide (63-87) probably forms alpha-helices
            which disrupt target cell membranes. {ECO:0000303|PubMed:16735513}.
            [PTM] Cleavage of the propeptide depends on the processing
            quadruplet motif (XXXR, with at least one of X being E).
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:27287558}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3071.5; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3074.0; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            01 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition: RecName: Full=Nemertide alpha-1; Flags: Precursor.
title:
TITLE     Peptide ion channel toxins from the bootlace worm, the longest
            animal on Earth
  TITLE     Functional Characterization of the Nemertide alpha Family of
            Peptide Toxins
  TITLE     Compound Heterozygous SCN5A Mutations in Severe Sodium
            Channelopathy With Brugada Syndrome: A Case Report
comment:
[FUNCTION] Highly potent toxin against insect sodium channel (Nav)
            and with less potent activity against mammalian sodium channels
            (PubMed:29567943). Potently inhibits inactivation of insect sodium
            channels of B.germanica (BgNav1) (EC(50)=8.6 nM), D.melanogaster
            (DmNav1), and arachnid sodium channel V.destructor (VdNav1)
            (PubMed:29567943, PubMed:34445875). Also delays the inactivation of
            most mammalian Nav channels tested (hNav1.1/SCN1A; EC(50)=124.1 nM,
            rNav1.2/SCN2A; EC(50)=359.6 nM, rNav1.3/SCN3A; EC(50)=135.4 nM,
            rNav1.4/SCN4A; EC(50)=145.5 nM, hNav1.5/SCN5A; EC(50)=138.3 nM,
            mNav1.6/SCN8A; EC(50)=240.4 nM, hNav1.9/SCN9A; EC(50)=76.5 nM)
            (PubMed:29567943, PubMed:34445875). 1 uM is enough to completely
            inhibits the inactivation, resulting in sustained non-inactivating
            currents (PubMed:29567943). In addition, the toxin significantly
            enhances the recovery from inactivation, and the open state is not
            required for the toxin to interact with the channel
            (PubMed:29567943). In vivo, injection into green crabs (Carcinus
            maenas at 1 mug/kg) of small doses (1-5 ug/kg) results in slow and
            fast permanent paralysis, whereas injection of high doses (more
            than 10 ug/kg) causes death (PubMed:29567943). Injection into
            juvenile Blaptica dubia cockroaches results in death or permanent
            paralysis at doses higher than 7.1 ug/kg (PubMed:29567943).
            Injection into brine shrimp (Artemia salina) stops movement or
            causes death after 24 hours (EC(50)=0.3 uM) (PubMed:34445875). In
            the rare inherited cardiac arrhythmia Brugada syndrome 1 (BRGDA1),
            this toxin is able to restore the loss of function by reducing
            channel inactivation, without affecting activation, by binding to
            Nav1.5/SCN5A (PubMed:32850980). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:29567943,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:32850980, ECO:0000269|PubMed:34445875}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000305|PubMed:29567943}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Confined to the epidermis and to the mucus
            layer. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:29567943}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:29567943}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3308.767; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:29567943}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not show effect on both
            human and rat Nav1.8/SCN10A. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:29567943,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:34445875}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] The primary and 3D structures of the mature peptide
            is identical to that of Nemertide alpha-1 from Lineus longissimus
            (AC P0DM24). Links to the 3D-structure (PDB=6ENA) is available in
            this entry. {ECO:0000305}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the nemertide family. {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=Lambda-theraphotoxin-Ec2c; Short=Lambda-TRTX-Ec2c;
AltName: Full=Kappa-theraphotoxin-Ec2c; Short=Kappa-TRTX-Ec2c.
title:
TITLE     A novel family of insect-selective peptide neurotoxins targeting
            insect large-conductance calcium-activated K+ channels isolated
            from the venom of the theraphosid spider Eucratoscelus constrictus
comment:
[FUNCTION] Both insecticidal and vertebrate neurotoxin that
            potently blocks insect calcium-activated potassium (BKCa) channels
            (Slo-type) in cockroach dorsal unpaired median (DUM) neurons
            (IC(50)=24.6 nM) (PubMed:21447641). This occurs in the absence of
            any shifts in the voltage dependence of activation
            (PubMed:21447641). May interact with the turret and/or loop region
            of the external entrance to the channel and does not project deeply
            into the pore of the channel (Probable). Also shows toxicity to
            mice by introcerebroventicular injection (PubMed:21447641).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:21447641, ECO:0000305|PubMed:21447641}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:21447641}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:21447641}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin.
            {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P83476}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3627.16; Method=MALDI; Note=Monoisotopic
            mass.; Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:21447641}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] Intrathoracical injection into juvenile crickets
            (Gryllus bimaculatus) of this toxin (at a dose of ca. 1100 pmol/g
            (4 ug/g)) causes a rapid insecticidal activity, with complete
            paralysis within 5 minutes and death within 15 minutes.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:21447641}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] Intracerebroventricular injection into mice of this
            toxin (at a dose of 1.8 ug per mice) causes strong neurotoxicity
            symptoms, including convulsions, tonic paralysis, general ataxia,
            extension of legs and toes, tail erection, and respiratory
            paralysis resulting in very marked cyanosis of the animal. These
            symptoms are reversible. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:21447641}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: At concentrations up to 330 nM,
            does not show activity on transient 'A-type' Kv, delayed-rectifier
            Kv, voltage-gated sodium channel (Nav) and both HVA and M-LVA Cav
            channels in cockroach DUM neurons. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:21447641}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the neurotoxin 30 (phrixotoxin) family.
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [CAUTION] This toxin has the prefix lambda in its name (instead of
            kappa), since lambda is the Greek letter attributed to
            calcium-activated potassium (KCa) channel impairing toxins
            (according to the nomenclature of King et al., 2008).
            {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=U2-agatoxin-Aop1a; Short=U2-AGTX-Aop1a; AltName:
Full=Agelenin.
title:
TITLE     Complete amino acid sequence of a new type of neurotoxin from the
            venom of the spider, Agelena opulenta
  TITLE     Agelenin, a spider neurotoxin: determination of the C-terminus as
            amide form, and investigation of the disulfide bond arrangement
  TITLE     Synthesis and disulfide structure determination of agelenin:
            identification of the carboxy-terminus as an amide form
  TITLE     Solution structure of agelenin, an insecticidal peptide isolated
            from the spider Agelena opulenta, and its structural similarities
            to insect-specific calcium channel inhibitors
comment:
On Dec 27, 2005 this sequence version replaced gi:482643.
            [FUNCTION] Insect-selective toxin causing rapid but reversible
            paralysis in crickets. Suppresses the excitatory postsynaptic
            potentials evoked in lobster neuromuscular synaptic preparations,
            possibly by blocking the presynaptic calcium channel (Cav). Induces
            instantaneous reversible paralysis when injected into crickets.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17644092}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 291 pmol/g of crickets.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17644092}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] The primary structure of the mature peptide is
            identical to that of U2-agatoxin-Ao1a (Agelenin) from Agelena
            orientalis (AC Q5Y4Y5). {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not inhibit mammalian
            Cav2.1/CACNA1A, Cav2.2/CACNA1B and Cav2.3/CACNA1E calcium channels.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:17644092}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the neurotoxin 01 (U2-agtx) family.

definition:
RecName: Full=U10-myrmicitoxin-Mri1b; Short=U10-MYRTX-Mri1b; Flags:
Precursor.
title:
TITLE     Venom Peptide Repertoire of the European Myrmicine Ant Manica
            rubida: Identification of Insecticidal Toxins
comment:
[FUNCTION] Induces paralysis after injection into blowflies
            (L.caesar), and then death within 24 hours (PubMed:32182430). May
            have antimicrobial properties, like most ant linear peptides (By
            similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:Q07932,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=2987.8; Method=Electrospray;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] LD(50) is 97.97 +-7.3 nmol/g in blowfly (L.caesar) (at
            24 hours post-injection). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 58.39 +-7.9 nmol/g in blowfly (L.caesar) (at
            1 hour post-injection). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 67.37 +-14 nmol/g in blowfly (L.caesar) (at
            24 hours post-injection). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32182430}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the formicidae venom precursor-01
            superfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition: RecName: Full=Toxin PhcrTx2.
title:
TITLE     PhcrTx2, a New Crab-Paralyzing Peptide Toxin from the Sea Anemone
            Phymanthus crucifer
comment:
[FUNCTION] Neurotoxin that induces paralysis (but not death) to
            U.thayeri crabs. Partially and reversibly inhibits glutamate-evoked
            peak currents (IC(50)=4.7 uM) but not voltage-gated potassium
            channel currents in cultured isolated neurons from the land snail
            H.aspersa. Weakly inhibits voltage-gated potassium peak currents
            (IC(50)=6.4 uM) and steady-state currents (IC(50)=8.2 uM) in rat
            dorsal root ganglion (DRG) neurons. Weakly inhibits voltage-gated
            sodium currents in rat DRG neurons (IC(50)=0.9 uM).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:29414882}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000305|PubMed:29414882}.
            Nematocyst {ECO:0000305|PubMed:29414882}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=5296.8; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:29414882}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 707 ug/kg in U.thayeri crabs.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:29414882}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no inhibitory effect on
            voltage-gated ion channels Kv1.1/KCNA1, Kv1.2/KCNA2, Kv1.3/KCNA3,
            Kv1.4/KCNA4, Kv1.6/KCNA6, Kv2.1/KCNB1, Kv3.1/KCNC1, Kv4.2/KCND2,
            Kv10.1/KCNH1/EAG1, Shaker IR (with the inactivation domain
            removed), Nav1.4/SCN4A, Nav1.5/SCN5A, Nav1.6/SCN8A or
            D.melanogaster Nav1/para. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:29414882}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemone type 3 (BDS) potassium
            channel toxin family. {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=Mambalgin-2; Short=Ma-2; Short=Mamb-2; AltName:
Full=Pi-Dp2.
title:
TITLE     Black mamba venom peptides target acid-sensing ion channels to
            abolish pain
  TITLE     Venom toxins in the exploration of molecular, physiological and
            pathophysiological functions of acid-sensing ion channels
  TITLE     Binding site and inhibitory mechanism of the mambalgin-2
            pain-relieving peptide on acid-sensing ion channel 1a
  TITLE     Total synthesis of mambalgin-1/2/3 by two-segment hydrazide-based
            native chemical ligation
  TITLE     Chemical synthesis, 3D structure, and ASIC binding site of the
            toxin mambalgin-2
comment:
[FUNCTION] This three-finger toxin inhibits ASIC channels. It acts
            as a gating modifier toxin by decreasing the apparent proton
            sensitivity of activation and by slightly increasing the apparent
            proton sensitivity for inactivation (PubMed:24695733). It binds
            more tightly to the closed state and to a much lesser extent the
            inactivated/desensitized state of ASIC1a isoform of ASIC1
            (PubMed:24695733). It interacts directly with the outside surface
            of the thumb domain of chicken ASIC1a (ASIC1a), but does not insert
            into the acidic pocket as suggested previously (By similarity).
            This binding leads to relocation of the thumb domain that could
            disrupt the acidic pocket of cASIC1a (By similarity). The peptide
            exerts both stimulatory and inhibitory effects on ASIC1a
            (PubMed:24695733). It reversibly inhibits rat ASIC1a (IC(50)=21-55
            nM), rat ASIC1b (IC(50)=103-192 nM), rat ASIC1a-ASIC1b (IC(50)=72
            nM), rat ASIC1a-ASIC2a (IC(50)=246-252 nM) and rat ASIC1a-ASIC2b
            (IC(50)=61 nM) (PubMed:23034652, PubMed:23624383, PubMed:24323786,
            PubMed:24695733, PubMed:26991634). In vivo, it shows a potent
            naloxone-resistant analgesic effect against acute and inflammatory
            pain upon central and peripheral injection (By similarity). In
            addition, it also has an opioid-independent effect on both thermal
            and mechanical inflammatory pain after systemic administration and
            is effective against neuropathic pain (By similarity).
            {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P0DKR6, ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:23624383, ECO:0000269|PubMed:24323786,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:24695733, ECO:0000269|PubMed:26991634}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland. {ECO:0000305}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=6538.4; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:23034652}.
            [PHARMACEUTICAL] Promising peptide that shows a potent analgesic
            effect against acute and inflammatory pain that can be as strong as
            morphine but resistant to naloxone, with much less tolerance and no
            respiratory distress. {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P0DKR6}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no effect on rat ASIC2a
            (PubMed:24695733). Has no effect on rat ASIC3, rat ASIC1a-ASIC3 and
            rat ASIC1b-ASIC3 channels, as well as on TRPV1, P2RX2 (P2X2), HTR3A
            (5-HT3A), Nav1.8 (SCN10A), Cav3.2 (CACNA1H) and Kv1.2 (KCNA2)
            channels (By similarity). Does not produce motor dysfunction,
            apathy, flaccid paralysis, convulsions or death upon central
            injections (intrathecal or intracerebroventricular) in mice (By
            similarity). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P0DKR6,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:24695733}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the snake three-finger toxin family.
            Short-chain subfamily. Mambalgin sub-subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Molecular diversification of peptide toxins from the tarantula
            Haplopelma hainanum (Ornithoctonus hainana) venom based on

  TITLE     Purification, sequencing and characterization of hainantoxin-VI, a
            neurotoxin from the Chinese bird spider Selenocosmia hainana
  TITLE     Mechanism of action of two insect toxins huwentoxin-III and
            hainantoxin-VI on voltage-gated sodium channels
comment:
On Dec 11, 2015 this sequence version replaced P0CH69.1.
            [FUNCTION] [Hainantoxin-VI]: Gating-modifier toxin that
            dose-dependently inhibits inactivation of voltage-gated sodium
            channels and reduces the peak of sodium current in cockroach DUM
            neurons (PubMed:20506577). In vivo, reversibly paralyzes

            preparation (Ref.2). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:20506577,
            ECO:0000269|Ref.2}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:20192277}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland. {ECO:0000305}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin. {ECO:0000250}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [U1-theraphotoxin-Hhn1a]: Mass=4057.6;
            Method=MALDI; Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:20192277}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [Hainantoxin-VI]: Mass=3998.8; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:20192277}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [Hainantoxin-VI]: Mass=3998.49; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|Ref.2}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the neurotoxin 10 (Hwtx-1) family. 24
            (Hwtx-6) subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

definition: RecName: Full=Mu-conotoxin SxIIIA.
title:
TITLE     NMR-based mapping of disulfide bridges in cysteine-rich peptides:
            application to the mu-conotoxin SxIIIA
  TITLE     mu-Conotoxins that differentially block sodium channels NaV1.1
            through 1.8 identify those responsible for action potentials in
            sciatic nerve
  TITLE     Alpha- and beta-subunit composition of voltage-gated sodium
            channels investigated with mu-conotoxins and the recently
            discovered muO section sign-conotoxin GVIIJ
comment:
[FUNCTION] Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).
            This synthetic toxin potently blocks rNav1.4/SCN4A (IC(50)= 7 nM).
            It also moderately blocks rNav1.1/SCN1A (IC(50)=370 nM),
            rNav1.2/SCN2A (IC(50)=1 uM), and mNav1.6/SCN6A (IC(50)=570 nM)
            (PubMed:18831583, PubMed:21652775). It is noteworthy that
            coexpression of subunits beta-2 or beta-4 (but not beta-1 or
            beta-3) decrease by more that 10-fold the binding potency of the
            toxin to rNav1.6 (PubMed:25632083). It is also noteworthy that the
            toxin is 50-fold more potent on mouse Nav1.6 than on rat Nav1.6
            (PubMed:25632083). In vivo, when injected intraperitoneally or
            subcutaneously in mice, causes motor impairment, paralysis and
            death (PubMed:18831583). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18831583,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:21652775}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000305|PubMed:18831583}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:18831583}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is III (CC-C-C-CC). Classified in
            the M-4 branch, since 4 residues stand between the fourth and the
            fifth cysteine residues. {ECO:0000305}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] When injected intraperitoneally or subcutaneously in
            mice, this toxin causes motor impairment/paralysis and is lethal at
            doses as low as 0.6 nmol per mouse. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18831583}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not inhibit rNav1.3/SCN3A,
            rNav1.5/SCN5A, rNav1.7/SCN9A and rNav1.8/SCN10A (PubMed:21652775,
            PubMed:25632083). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:21652775,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:25632083}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin M superfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

comment:
On Jul 11, 2006 this sequence version replaced gi:22001576.
            [FUNCTION] Mu-conotoxins block voltage-gated sodium channels (Nav).
            This toxin potently blocks rNav1.4/SCN4A (IC(50)=36-41 nM)
            (PubMed:10627583, PubMed:21652775). It also moderately blocks
            rNav1.1/SCN1A (IC(50)=120 nM), rNav1.2/SCN2A (IC(50)=620 nM),
            rNav1.3/SCN3A (IC(50)=3.2 uM), mNav1.6/SCN8A (IC(50)=100 nM)
            (PubMed:10627583, PubMed:21652775). This inhibition is reversible.
            The block of Nav1.1, Nav1.2, and Nav1.6 is modified when
            beta-subunits are coexpressed with alpha subunits. Hence, blocks of
            channels containing the beta-1 and beta-3 subunits are more potent
            (compared to channels without beta subunits), whereas blocks of
            channels containing the beta-2 and beta-4 are less potent (compared
            to channels without beta subunits). In vivo, this peptide causes
            flaccid paralysis in both mice and fish.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10627583, ECO:0000269|PubMed:18950653,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:21652775, ECO:0000269|PubMed:22229737,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22407516, ECO:0000269|PubMed:23146020}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:P01523}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:9614224}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is III (CC-C-C-CC). Classified in
            the M-4 branch, since 4 residues stand between the fourth and the
            fifth cysteine residues. {ECO:0000305}.
            [PTM] 3D-structure of 3 disulfide-bond connectivities isomers is
            described (PIIIA-1 (C1-C5, C2-C6, C3-C4), PIIIA-2 (C1-C4, C2-C5,
            C3-C6) and PIIIA-3 (C1-C2, C3-C4, C5-C6)) (PubMed:22407516). Only
            PIIIA-2 contains the cysteine connectivity described as typical for
            native mu-conotoxins. However, PIIIA-1 is more potent than PIIIA-2,
            suggesting another possible disulfid connectivity. For this reason,
            both connectivities have been indicated in features.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:22407516}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Exists in two forms, due to cis-trans isomerization
            at Hyp-57. Adopts a predominately trans conformation (Probable).
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:12006587}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not or only weakly blocks
            rNav1.5/SCN5A, rNav1.7/SCN9A (IC(50)=3.1-6.2 uM and >100 uM), and
            rNav1.8/SCN10A. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10627583,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:21652775}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin M superfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Mechanisms for evolving hypervariability: the case of conopeptides
  TITLE     A molluscivorous Conus toxin: conserved frameworks in conotoxins
  TITLE     Mollusc-specific toxins from the venom of Conus textile neovicarius
  TITLE     Rapid sensitive analysis of cysteine rich peptide venom components
  TITLE     Alteration of sodium currents by new peptide toxins from the venom
            of a molluscivorous Conus snail
  TITLE     A new neurotoxin receptor site on sodium channels is identified by
            a conotoxin that affects sodium channel inactivation in molluscs
            and acts as an antagonist in rat brain
  TITLE     Secretion and maturation of conotoxins in the venom ducts of Conus
            textile
  TITLE     Three-dimensional solution structure of the sodium channel
            agonist/antagonist delta-conotoxin TxVIA
comment:
[FUNCTION] Delta-conotoxins bind to site 6 of voltage-gated sodium
            channels (Nav) and inhibit the inactivation process. Binding of
            this toxin is strongly calcium-dependent but not voltage-dependent.
            The binding site is most likely on the extracellular side of the
            sodium channel. Binds receptor sites on both mollusk and rat
            central nervous system, but despite its high affinity binding to
            rat sodium channel, it has no functional effect in vivo and in
            vitro on it. Has also no effect on Gambusia fish. Is important in
            mollusk for the paralysis of the prey. Upon injection of the
            peptide, a subordinate lobster assumes an exaggerated dominant
            posture (of a 'King-Kong' lobster!). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1761058,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:2706261, ECO:0000269|PubMed:8261090,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:8300586}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:1761058,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:19380747, ECO:0000269|PubMed:2706261}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom duct. Is present in all
            duct parts with a highest content in part 4 (distal part near the
            pharynx). {ECO:0000305|PubMed:1761058, ECO:0000305|PubMed:19380747,
            ECO:0000305|PubMed:23031820, ECO:0000305|PubMed:2706261}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:12145313}.
            [DOMAIN] The cysteine framework is VI/VII (C-C-CC-C-C).
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3034.2; Mass_error=0.05;
            Method=Electrospray; Note=Without oxidation at Met-59.;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:19380747}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3050.189; Mass_error=0.05;
            Method=Electrospray; Note=With oxidation at Met-59.;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:19380747}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Veratridine increases the rate of dissociation in a
            dose-dependent manner.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the conotoxin O1 superfamily.
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [CAUTION] Several genes are coding for this toxin for which the
            structure by NMR has been determined. The cross-references to PDB
            can be found in entry AC P18511. {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Latarcins, antimicrobial and cytolytic peptides from the venom of
            the spider Lachesana tarabaevi (Zodariidae) that exemplify
            biomolecular diversity
  TITLE     Lachesana tarabaevi, an expert in membrane-active toxins
comment:
[FUNCTION] Does not have antimicrobial or antifungal activity. Does
            not have hemolytic activity against rabbit erythrocytes. However,
            it causes some conductance changes in planar bilayer membranes,
            without membrane rupture, suggesting a cytolytic function on other
            biological targets. It causes paralysis, but is not lethal when
            injected into insect (M.domestica) larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:16735513}.
            [DOMAIN] The mature peptide (64-97) probably forms alpha-helices
            which disrupt target cell membranes. {ECO:0000303|PubMed:16735513}.
            [PTM] Cleavage of the propeptide depends on the processing
            quadruplet motif (XXXR, with at least one of X being E).
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:27287558}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=3942.9; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            07 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

title:
TITLE     Latarcins, antimicrobial and cytolytic peptides from the venom of

comment:
[FUNCTION] It has antimicrobial activity against Gram-positive
            bacteria (A.globiformis VKM Ac-1112 (MIC=0.7 uM), and B.subtilis
            VKM B-501 (MIC=2.9 uM)), Gram-negative bacteria (E.coli DH5-alpha
            (MIC=23 uM), E.coli MH1 (MIC=28 uM), and P.aeruginosa PAO1 (MIC>45
            uM)), and yeasts (P.pastoris GS115 (MIC=23 uM), and S.cerevisiae
            Y190 (MIC=23 uM)). Does not have hemolytic against rabbit
            erythrocytes. Causes paralysis, but is not lethal when injected
            into insect (M.domestica) larvae. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:16735513, ECO:0000305|PubMed:27287558}.
            [DOMAIN] The mature peptide (62-81) probably forms alpha-helices
            which disrupt target cell membranes. {ECO:0000303|PubMed:16735513}.
            [PTM] Cleavage of the propeptide depends on the processing
            quadruplet motif (XXXR, with at least one of X being E).
            {ECO:0000303|PubMed:27287558}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=2424.6; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:16735513}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=2426.0; Method=MALDI;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:27287558}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the cationic peptide 03 (latarcin) family.
            03 subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.

Full=Peptide CogiTx1; Flags: Precursor.
title:
TITLE     CogiTx1: A novel subtilisin A inhibitor isolated from the sea
            anemone Condylactis gigantea belonging to the defensin 4 protein
            family
comment:
[FUNCTION] Neurotoxin that induces paralysis when injected into
            crabs (By similarity). May function in antimicrobial activity as it
            displays inhibitory activity towards the B.licheniformis enzyme
            subtilisin A (SUBTA) and the recombinant S.maltophilia protease 1
            (rStmPr1) enzyme (Ref.1). Also displays inhibitory activity against
            various proteases including the porcine pancreatic elastase (PPE)
            and proteinase K (PK) (Ref.1). {ECO:0000250|UniProtKB:C0HK75,
            ECO:0000269|Ref.1}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|Ref.1}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=4970.68; Method=Electrospray;
            Evidence={ECO:0000269|Ref.1}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not show any inhibitory
            activity against chymotrypsin, trypsin or papain.
            {ECO:0000269|Ref.1}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemone type 3 (BDS) potassium
            channel toxin family. {ECO:0000305}.

definition: RecName: Full=Kappa-actitoxin-Ate1a; Short=Ate1a.
title:
TITLE     PHAB toxins: a unique family of predatory sea anemone toxins
            evolving via intra-gene concerted evolution defines a new peptide
            fold
comment:
[FUNCTION] Voltage-gated potassium channel inhibitor that is
            certainly used for prey capture (PubMed:30109357). It inhibits
            several potassium channels, but not all (Kv1.1/KCNA1 (IC(50)=353
            nM), Kv1.2/KCNA2 (IC(50)=146 nM), Kv1.3/KCNA3 (IC(50)=3051 nM),
            Kv1.6/KCNA6 (IC(50)=191 nM), and Shaker IR (23% inhibition at 3
            uM)) (PubMed:30109357). In vivo, injection of this toxin into
            amphipods results in impaired swimming followed by contractile
            paralysis (PubMed:30109357). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:30109357}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:30109357}.
            Nematocyst {ECO:0000305|PubMed:30109357}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by tentacle.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:30109357}.
            [DOMAIN] Adopts the three-dimensional structure 'proline-hinged
            asymmetric beta-hairpin-like' (PHAB) fold.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:30109357}.
            [DOMAIN] The prepropeptide contains 10 domains separated by dibasic
            cleavage sites: a signal peptide, three cysteine-containing
            propeptide domains (CysPro), three cysteine-free propeptide domains
            (LinearPro) and three Kappa-actitoxin-Ate1a (PHAB) domains. The
            sequence 'CysPro-LinearPro-PHAB' is repeated three times.
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:30109357}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] Mass=1887.93; Method=MALDI; Note=Monoisotopic
            mass.; Evidence={ECO:0000269|PubMed:30109357}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: does not show antimicrobial
            activity (when 256 ug/mL are tested on E.coli, K.pneumoniae,
            A.baumannii, P.aeruginosa, and S.aureus, as well as on fungi
            C.albicans and C.neoformans) (PubMed:30109357). Is not cytotoxic or
            cytolytic against cultured human cancer cell lines and erythrocytes
            (PubMed:30109357). It shows only a weak affinity for lipid
            membranes (PubMed:30109357). It has no effect on Kv1.4/KCNA4,
            Kv1.5/KCNA5, Kv2.1/KCNB1, Kv3.1/KCNC1, Kv4.2/KCND2, Kv7.2/KCNQ2,
            and Kv11.1/KCNH2/ERG1 (PubMed:30109357).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:30109357}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemonne PHAB family.
            {ECO:0000305}.

definition:
RecName: Full=N.vectensis toxin 1 7; Short=Nv1; AltName:
Full=Neurotoxin Nv1-116.41.1; Flags: Precursor.
reference:
PUBMED   17615350
PUBMED   18538344
PUBMED   18222944
PUBMED   22048953
PUBMED   29424690
PUBMED   31134275
title:
TITLE     Sea anemone genome reveals ancestral eumetazoan gene repertoire and
            genomic organization
  TITLE     Intron retention as a posttranscriptional regulatory mechanism of
            neurotoxin expression at early life stages of the starlet anemone
            Nematostella vectensis
  TITLE     Concerted evolution of sea anemone neurotoxin genes is revealed
            through analysis of the Nematostella vectensis genome
  TITLE     Neurotoxin localization to ectodermal gland cells uncovers an
            alternative mechanism of venom delivery in sea anemones
  TITLE     Dynamics of venom composition across a complex life cycle
  TITLE     The Birth and Death of Toxins with Distinct Functions: A Case Study
            in the Sea Anemone Nematostella
comment:
[FUNCTION] Binds to site 3 of voltage-gated sodium channels and
            inhibits the inactivation process (PubMed:18538344). Is highly
            active on DmNav1/TipE (drosophila) and is only extremely weakly
            active on rat Nav1.4-beta-1/SCN4A-SCN1B, and on human
            Nav1.5-beta-1/SCN5A-beta-1 (PubMed:18538344). This reveals high
            specificity for arthropod over mammalian channels
            (PubMed:18538344). In vivo, when released into the medium, this
            recombinant toxin induces impaired swimming, paralysis and death of
            the crustacean A.nauplii within several hours (PubMed:22048953).
            Also causes paralysis of cherry shrimps immediately after injection
            at very low doses (PubMed:29424690). Its effect on zebrafish
            (D.rerio) larvae is also rapid, since it induces tail twitching
            accompanied by impaired swimming after 20 minutes and complete
            paralysis within 45 minutes (PubMed:22048953). It has also been
            observed to cause death of zebrafish larvae within 1 hour
            (PubMed:31134275). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [ALTERNATIVE PRODUCTS] Event=Alternative splicing; Named
            isoforms=2; Comment=Intron retention discovered for all
            transcripts, no experimental confirmation available for this
            specific sequence.; Name=1; IsoId=A7SCE5-1; Sequence=Displayed;
            Name=2; Synonyms=truncated; IsoId=A7SCE5-2; Sequence=VSP_039751.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed in ectodermal glands and in clumps
            outside of the extodermal layer (PubMed:22048953). Is not expressed
            in nematocytes (PubMed:22048953). In adult female tissues, shows
            similar expression levels in mesenteries (gametes-producing
            tissue), tentacles, pharynx and physa (PubMed:29424690).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690}.
            [DEVELOPMENTAL STAGE] Is detected in unfertilized eggs (at protein
            level) (PubMed:29424690, PubMed:31134275). Is also detected in late
            planulae, primary polyps and adults (both females and males) (at
            protein level) (PubMed:22048953, PubMed:29424690). Nv1 is
            transcribed throughout the complete life cycle and is found at
            multiple developmental stages including unfertilized eggs,
            blastulae, gastrulae, early planulae, planulae, metamorphosing
            planulae, primary polyps, juvenile polyps (2 and 4 months old),
            adult males, and adult females, with highest levels in juvenile
            polyps and adults (PubMed:18538344, PubMed:29424690). Importantly,
            Nv1 transcripts are not spliced in the embryo and planula due to
            intron retention and therefore Nv1 can be considered purely an
            adult toxin (PubMed:18538344). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 76 nmol/kg into blowfly larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Nv1 toxin seems to be encoded by 8 different genes.
            4 of them code for identical precursors, whereas 4 others code for
            very similar precursors. In the genome draft, 6 additional loci are
            also correlated to Nv1 toxin, but they are not predicted to be
            functional genes. This high similarity may be explained by
            concerted evolution.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] The primary structure of the mature peptide is
            identical in 9 entries (AC B1NWS4, AC B1NWS1, AC B1NWR6, AC P0CH90,
            AC P0CH46, AC B1NWS8, AC A7SCE5, AC B1NWR7 and AC P0CH45).
            Additional information can be found in entry AC B1NWS4.
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] [Isoform 2]: Due to an intron retention observed
            only in early life stages (embryo and planula). {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no activity on the rat brain
            channel Nav1.2a-beta-1/SCN2A-SCN1B. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemone sodium channel inhibitory
            toxin family. Type II subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
            [SEQUENCE CAUTION] Sequence=EDO38675.1; Type=Erroneous gene model
            prediction; Evidence={ECO:0000305}.

            blastulae, gastrulae, early planulae, planulae, metamorphosing
            planulae, primary polyps, juvenile polyps (2 and 4 months old),
            adult males, and adult females, with highest levels in juvenile
            polyps and adults (PubMed:18538344, PubMed:29424690). Importantly,
            Nv1 transcripts are not spliced in the embryo and planula due to
            intron retention and therefore Nv1 can be considered purely an
            adult toxin (PubMed:18538344). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 76 nmol/kg into blowfly larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Nv1 toxin seems to be encoded by 8 different genes.
            4 of them code for identical precursors, whereas 4 others code for
            very similar precursors. In the genome draft, 6 additional loci are
            also correlated to Nv1 toxin, but they are not predicted to be
            functional genes. This high similarity may be explained by
            concerted evolution.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] The primary structure of the mature peptide is
            identical in 9 entries (AC B1NWS4, AC B1NWS1, AC B1NWR6, AC P0CH90,
            AC P0CH46, AC B1NWS8, AC A7SCE5, AC B1NWR7 and AC P0CH45).
            Additional information can be found in entry AC B1NWS4.
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] [Isoform 2]: Due to an intron retention observed
            only in early life stages (embryo and planula). {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no activity on the rat brain
            channel Nav1.2a-beta-1/SCN2A-SCN1B. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemone sodium channel inhibitory
            toxin family. Type II subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
            [SEQUENCE CAUTION] Sequence=EDO38673.1; Type=Erroneous gene model
            prediction; Evidence={ECO:0000305}.

comment:
[FUNCTION] Binds to site 3 of voltage-gated sodium channels and
            inhibits the inactivation process (PubMed:18538344). Is highly
            active on DmNav1/TipE (drosophila) and is only extremely weakly
            active on rat Nav1.4-beta-1/SCN4A-SCN1B, and on human
            Nav1.5-beta-1/SCN5A-beta-1 (PubMed:18538344). This reveals high
            specificity for arthropod over mammalian channels
            (PubMed:18538344). In vivo, when released into the medium, this
            recombinant toxin induces impaired swimming, paralysis and death of
            the crustacean A.nauplii within several hours (PubMed:22048953).
            Also causes paralysis of cherry shrimps immediately after injection
            at very low doses (PubMed:29424690). Its effect on zebrafish
            (D.rerio) larvae is also rapid, since it induces tail twitching
            accompanied by impaired swimming after 20 minutes and complete
            paralysis within 45 minutes (PubMed:22048953). It has also been
            observed to cause death of zebrafish larvae within 1 hour
            (PubMed:31134275). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [ALTERNATIVE PRODUCTS] Event=Alternative splicing; Named
            isoforms=2; Comment=Intron retention discovered for all
            transcripts, no experimental confirmation available for this
            specific sequence.; Name=1; IsoId=P0CH90-1; Sequence=Displayed;
            Name=2; Synonyms=truncated; IsoId=P0CH90-2; Sequence=VSP_039749.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed in ectodermal glands and in clumps
            outside of the extodermal layer (PubMed:22048953). Is not expressed
            in nematocytes (PubMed:22048953). In adult female tissues, shows
            similar expression levels in mesenteries (gametes-producing
            tissue), tentacles, pharynx and physa (PubMed:29424690).
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690}.
            [DEVELOPMENTAL STAGE] Is detected in unfertilized eggs (at protein
            level) (PubMed:29424690, PubMed:31134275). Is also detected in late
            planulae, primary polyps and adults (both females and males) (at
            protein level) (PubMed:22048953, PubMed:29424690). Nv1 is
            transcribed throughout the complete life cycle and is found at
            multiple developmental stages including unfertilized eggs,
            blastulae, gastrulae, early planulae, planulae, metamorphosing
            planulae, primary polyps, juvenile polyps (2 and 4 months old),
            adult males, and adult females, with highest levels in juvenile
            polyps and adults (PubMed:18538344, PubMed:29424690). Importantly,
            Nv1 transcripts are not spliced in the embryo and planula due to
            intron retention and therefore Nv1 can be considered purely an
            adult toxin (PubMed:18538344). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22048953, ECO:0000269|PubMed:29424690,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:31134275}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] PD(50) is 76 nmol/kg into blowfly larvae.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Nv1 toxin seems to be encoded by 8 different genes.
            4 of them code for identical precursors, whereas 4 others code for
            very similar precursors. In the genome draft, 6 additional loci are
            also correlated to Nv1 toxin, but they are not predicted to be
            functional genes. This high similarity may be explained by
            concerted evolution.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] The primary structure of the mature peptide is
            identical in 9 entries (AC B1NWS4, AC B1NWS1, AC B1NWR6, AC P0CH90,
            AC P0CH46, AC B1NWS8, AC A7SCE5, AC B1NWR7 and AC P0CH45).
            Additional information can be found in entry AC B1NWS4.
            {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] [Isoform 2]: Due to an intron retention observed
            only in early life stages (embryo and planula). {ECO:0000305}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] Negative results: has no activity on the rat brain
            channel Nav1.2a-beta-1/SCN2A-SCN1B. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:18538344}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the sea anemone sodium channel inhibitory
            toxin family. Type II subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
            [SEQUENCE CAUTION] Sequence=EDO38671.1; Type=Erroneous gene model
            prediction; Evidence={ECO:0000305}.

comment:
On Feb 8, 2013 this sequence version replaced P81694.1.
            [FUNCTION] [Toxin CSTX-1]: Spider venom toxin that shows calcium
            channel blocking activity and exhibits cytolytic activity by
            affecting the outer leaflet curvature and/or pore formation across
            the membrane (PubMed:22613721, PubMed:32290562). It blocks L-type
            calcium channels (Cav1/CACNA1) in mammalian neurons at nanomolar
            concentrations. Furthermore, it produces a slow voltage-independent
            block of mid/low and high voltage-activated calcium channels in
            cockroach neurons (PubMed:17517422). Potassium ions, histamine,
            M-ctenitoxin-Cs1a (AC P83619), CSTX-9 (AC P58604), and CSTX-13 (AC
            P83919) synergistically increase the insecticidal activity of this
            toxin (PubMed:15914655, PubMed:32290562). In vivo, it causes
            paralysis in blow flies and provokes death in drosophila
            (PubMed:32290562). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:17517422,
            ECO:0000269|PubMed:22613721, ECO:0000269|PubMed:32290562}.
            [FUNCTION] [Toxin CSTX-2a]: Blocks voltage-activated calcium
            channels (Cav) (By similarity). Does not induce cell membrane
            permeability increase when tested on Xenopus oocytes. No
            alpha-helical structures are detectable. Is 7-fold less neurotoxic
            than omega-ctenitoxin-Cs1a on drosophila flies. {ECO:0000250}.
            [FUNCTION] [Toxin CSTX-2b]: Blocks voltage-activated calcium
            channels (Cav) (By similarity). Is 190-fold less neurotoxic than
            omega-ctenitoxin-Cs1a on drosophila flies. {ECO:0000250}.
            [SUBUNIT] Monomer (Probable). Interacts with CSTX-13 (AC P83919)
            (Kd=430 nM), but does not interact with CSTX-9 (AC P58604)
            (PubMed:32290562). {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32290562, ECO:0000305}.
            [SUBCELLULAR LOCATION] Secreted {ECO:0000269|PubMed:8016851}.
            Target cell membrane {ECO:0000305|PubMed:32290562}.
            [TISSUE SPECIFICITY] Expressed by the venom gland.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10772256}.
            [DOMAIN] The presence of a 'disulfide through disulfide knot'
            structurally defines this protein as a knottin. {ECO:0000250}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [Toxin CSTX-1]: Mass=8352.62;
            Method=Electrospray; Evidence={ECO:0000269|Ref.4}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [Toxin CSTX-2a]: Mass=6865.75;
            Method=Electrospray; Evidence={ECO:0000269|Ref.4}.
            [MASS SPECTROMETRY] [Toxin CSTX-2b]: Mass=6709.57;
            Method=Electrospray; Evidence={ECO:0000269|Ref.4}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] [Toxin CSTX-1]: LD(50) is 0.535 pmol/mg when
            intrathoracically injected into drosophila.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10897091}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] [Toxin CSTX-1]: LD(50) is 0.432 pmol/mg when
            intrathoracically co-injected with CSTX-9 (AC P58604) into
            drosophila. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32290562}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] [Toxin CSTX-1]: LD(50) is 0.075 pmol/mg when
            intrathoracically co-injected with CSTX-13 (AC P83919) into
            drosophila. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:32290562}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] [Toxin CSTX-2a]: LD(50) is 2.58 pmol/mg on Drosophila.
            {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10897091}.
            [TOXIC DOSE] [Toxin CSTX-2b]: LD(50) is 66.51 pmol/mg on
            Drosophila. {ECO:0000269|PubMed:10897091}.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] [Toxin CSTX-1]: is the most abundant neurotoxin in
            the venom of C.salei.
            [MISCELLANEOUS] [Toxin CSTX-1]: Negative results: has no
            antimicrobial activity against E.coli (ATCC 25922) and S.aureus
            (ATCC29213). Surprisingly, it destroys the E.coli mutant (SBS363)
            in a concentration of 31.25 uM (PubMed:22613721).
            {ECO:0000305|PubMed:22613721}.
            [SIMILARITY] Belongs to the neurotoxin 19 (CSTX) family. 04
            (U1-Lctx) subfamily. {ECO:0000305}.
